{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501303"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:27:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:27:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1743"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1743"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.06,0.02,0.69,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115249"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1743"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97256"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"731"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3056"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48839"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115249"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-hour episode of sudden palpitations and dizziness earlier today. He checked his smart watch at the time, which showed a pulse rate of 180/min. The episode occurred while he was sitting at his desk at work. He denies chest pain or shortness of breath and currently feels well. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He does not smoke and drinks alcohol socially. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 78/min and regular, blood pressure 128/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable. A 12\u2011lead ECG on arrival is obtained (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for his palpitations?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cardiac ischaemia","Mutation of cardiac sodium gene","Complete heart block","Presence of accessory tract","Ventricular hypertrophy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVentricular pre-excitation is characterised on the electrocardiogram by a short PR interval and an initial slurred upstroke of the QRS complex (delta wave). These features reflect early ventricular activation via an atrioventricular bypass tract that conducts outside the atrioventricular node. The key distinction is between Wolff\u2011Parkinson\u2011White pattern (the electrocardiogram finding alone) and Wolff\u2011Parkinson\u2011White syndrome (the pattern plus symptomatic tachyarrhythmias such as paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia, atrial flutter or atrial fibrillation). This patient reports paroxysmal palpitations with a recorded rapid pulse and has an electrocardiogram consistent with pre-excitation, supporting Wolff\u2011Parkinson\u2011White syndrome due to an accessory pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresence of accessory tract\u003C/strong\u003E best explains his presentation. An atrioventricular bypass tract (often termed the Bundle of Kent) allows conduction that bypasses the atrioventricular node, creating the substrate for atrioventricular re-entry tachycardia and for rapid conduction of atrial arrhythmias, which can cause palpitations, dizziness, and syncope. Definitive management is catheter ablation of the pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac ischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can cause palpitations, but the resting electrocardiogram in Wolff\u2011Parkinson\u2011White may mimic ischaemia without true coronary disease. In this case, the history lacks chest pain or risk features, and the pre-excitation pattern provides a more direct explanation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMutation of cardiac sodium gene\u003C/strong\u003E refers to channelopathies such as Brugada syndrome, which show coved ST elevation in V1\u2013V2 and typically present with syncope or nocturnal agonal respirations rather than pre-excitation with a delta wave.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete heart block\u003C/strong\u003E presents with bradycardia, atrioventricular dissociation, and often presyncope, not paroxysmal tachycardia; it does not produce a short PR interval or delta wave.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E may alter QRS voltages and repolarisation but does not cause a short PR interval with a delta wave; pre-excitation can sometimes mimic right ventricular hypertrophy patterns, but the mechanism is conduction via an accessory pathway.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A short PR interval with a delta wave indicates ventricular pre-excitation; Wolff-Parkinson-White pattern is the ECG finding, whereas Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome is the pattern plus symptomatic tachyarrhythmias."],"references":["Hampton, JR. The ECG made easy. 8th ed. Toronto: Churchill Livingstone Elsevier. 2013. p. 152-4.","Al-Khatib SM, Pritchett ELC. Clinical features of Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome. Am Heart J. 1999 Sep 1;138(3):403\u201313.","Sieira J, Brugada P. The definition of the Brugada syndrome. Eur Heart J. 2017 Oct 21;38(40):3029\u201334."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97256"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1743"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14617"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14617"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bdb35d8f-22bf-4508-a90a-9d2a3ba2b362.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bdb35d8f-22bf-4508-a90a-9d2a3ba2b362.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":583,"height":317}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97256"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T10:37:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T10:59:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1743"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115249"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":nu